"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007149","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-23","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) closely scrutinises activity on the Preston New Road site, working with its fellow regulators. HSE visits sites on the basis of identified risk. HSE has made four site visits to the Preston New Road site before hydraulic fracturing commenced, including an inspection of the high-pressure equipment on 3 and 4 October 2018. HSE has not visited the site since 4 November 2018.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-23T11:30:30.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007149/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007149/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-14","Fracking: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether any staff of the Health and Safety Executive have visited the Preston New Road shale gas site since the four seismic events of greater than the red light 0.5ML threshold that occurred between 26 October 2018 and 4 November 2018.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","191380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007151","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-22","<p>The information is not centrally held and could obtained only at disproportionate cost. However, all pregnant women in custody have an individual care and management plan that is communicated to all staff and all pregnant women are seen by a mid-wife at least fortnightly or as required.</p><p>Healthcare in prisons is provided by trained medics and nurses, but we have also made training on dealing with pregnant women available to all prison officers.</p><p>We know it is extremely rare for a woman to give birth in prison - because every step is taken to get them to hospital - but those unique cases are invariably down to the unpredictability of labour.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-11-22T16:18:17.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007151/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007151/answer","Charnwood","Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007151/answer/previousversion/85803","Biography information for Edward Argar","54","Justice","Justice","2018-11-14","Prisoners: Childbirth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women have given birth in prison in each year since 2015; and what proportion of those women had an appropriately trained medical professional present at the birth.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","191472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007152","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-20","<p>The inclusion of a requirement to carry out the six-week maternal postnatal check for all mothers in the general medical services contract would need to be negotiated and agreed, as part of the annual contract negotiations. We have asked for this issue to be considered in the contract negotiations for 2019/20. The negotiations are expected to be concluded before the end of the year. The details of those negotiations are not generally discussed until an agreement on the way forward has been reached.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-20T11:25:47.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007152/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007152/answer","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007152/answer/previousversion/85824","Biography information for Steve Brine","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-14","Postnatal Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he plans to include a maternal six-week check in the new General Medical Services contract; and when the current negotiations will conclude.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","191473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007153","Department for Education","false","2018-11-19","<p>Prior to 2018-19, local authorities were free to determine the balance of funding between their schools, high needs and early years budgets, all funded from the Dedicated Schools Grant (DSG). It is not possible to give figures for transfers from the schools block to high needs, as the precise amounts spent by local authorities will also be affected by transfers to and from DSG reserves, and any funding from other sources (for instance, local authorities’ general funds) spent on educational purposes.</p><p>In 2018-19, with the introduction of the national funding formulae for schools and high needs, we have limited this flexibility in order to ensure that the majority of schools funding that local authorities receive is going directly to schools.</p><p>Local authorities are able to move up to 0.5% of their funding from the schools block to the high needs block, with agreement of their schools forum. This is explained in the high needs operational guide, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/high-needs-funding-arrangements-2019-to-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/high-needs-funding-arrangements-2019-to-2020</a>. Where a local authority wishes to move more funding, or the forum does not agree to the transfer, the local authority will be required to seek recourse to my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Education. Last year, after thorough consideration, 13 local authorities were granted the ability to move funding under these circumstances.</p><p>We will publish data shortly showing the amount of schools block funding the local authorities has allocated this year, compared to the amount they received, thereby providing an indication of funding directed to other areas, such as high needs.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-11-19T17:18:42.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007153/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007153/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-11-14","Special Educational Needs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much money was reallocated from the Dedicated Schools Grant towards the High Needs Block in each local authority area in England in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","191474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007155","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-19","<p>Consultant-led non-urgent mental health treatments are covered by the general National Health Service 18 week waiting time standard.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, in 2016 NHS England published the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health which includes the following waiting times targets for mental health services, to be achieved by 2020/21:</p><p>- For accessing ‘Improving Access to Psychological Therapies’ services 75% of referrals should be seen within six weeks and 95% should be seen within 18 weeks;</p><p>- For eating disorder services 95% of referrals should be seen within four weeks for routine cases and 95% of urgent referrals should be seen within one week; and</p><p>- For the Early Intervention in Psychosis programme 50% of people experiencing a first episode of psychosis should start a National Institute for Health and Care Excellence recommended package of care within two weeks of referral, rising to 60%.</p><p> </p><p>We are on track to meet these targets, which are tracked on the Five Year Forward View dashboard, available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/mental-health-five-year-forward-view-dashboard/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/mental-health-five-year-forward-view-dashboard/</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-19T17:38:36.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007155/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007155/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-14","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what guidance his Department has provided to Child and adolescent mental health services on acceptable waiting times for clinical assessments from the date of referral.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","191475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007156","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-20","<p>The information requested on the number of individuals of pensionable age in receipt of either Attendance Allowance (AA), Disability Living Allowance (DLA) or Personal Independence Payment (PIP), or Pension Credit (PC) in Wansbeck Constituency is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-11-20T14:38:19.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007156/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007156/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-14","Pensioners: Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people of pensionable age in Wansbeck Constituency are in receipt of (a) attendance allowance, (b) disability living allowance or personal independence payment and (c) pension credits.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","191419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007157","Department for Education","false","2018-11-19","<p>The department will be running a public consultation regarding the funding of the rise in employer contributions for the Teachers’ Pension Scheme and has already agreed to delay the introduction of these changes until September 2019. The department will use the consultation to better understand the impact of the proposed changes on the affected English higher education institutions to decide what, if any, action should be taken.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-11-19T16:34:54.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007157/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007157/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-11-14","Teachers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing a phasing in period for higher education Institutions to implement the increased contribution to the teachers pension scheme.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","191299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007158","Department for Education","false","2018-11-22","<p>As all of the academies that were part of Wakefield City Academies Trust have now transferred to new trusts, the Education and Skills Funding Agency published its report of the multi‑academy trust review, carried out in 2016, on 15 November 2018 on GOV.UK. A copy of the report has been placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-11-22T16:43:07.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007158/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007158/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-11-14","Wakefield City Academies Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the answer of 4 September 2018 to Question 168016 on Wakefield City Academies Trust, whether he plans to publish the Education and Skills Funding Agency report into Wakefield City Academies Trust after all the schools are transferred to new trusts.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","191432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007159","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-19","<p>I refer the honourable Member to the reply to UIN <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=179316" target="_blank">179316</a> on 18 October.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-11-19T12:15:39.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007159/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007159/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-11-14","Universal Credit: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason a student maintenance loan is classed as income in respect of applications for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","191476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007160","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-19","<p>The Government has assured the Overseas Territories of our commitment to working collaboratively with them on the introduction of public registers. Minister of State Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon has already proposed the establishment of a UK- Overseas Territories technical working group to meet in early 2019 and will discuss more formally the implementation timetable and any initial requests for support at the Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council next month.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-19T15:56:13.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007160/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007160/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-11-14","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department has taken since the passing of the Sanctions and Anti-Money Laundering Act 2018 to ensure that British Overseas Territories introduce public registers of beneficial ownership.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","191477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007162","Home Office","false","2018-11-19","<p>The Home Office leads on the Government’s relationship with the Crown Dependencies on beneficial ownership. The Crown Dependencies have confirmed they will develop public registers of company beneficial ownership once it has been established as a global norm.</p><p>The Government recently launched the global beneficial ownership transparency campaign to shift the global norms on beneficial ownership transparency by 2023.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2018-11-19T16:55:12.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007162/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007162/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-11-14","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps his Department has taken since the passing of the Sanctions and Anti-Money Laundering Act 2018 to encourage Crown dependencies to introduce public registers of beneficial ownership.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","191478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007163","Treasury","false","2018-11-19","<p>Beneficial ownership registers are outside of the scope of a double taxation treaty and so did not feature in the negotiations with Jersey, Guernsey or the Isle of Man. Double taxation treaties are based on the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development’s Model Tax Convention, which does not include beneficial ownership registers.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-11-19T15:54:53.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007163/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007163/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-14","Double Taxation: Crown Dependencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department took steps to seek to include an increase in transparency for beneficial ownership registers in the negotiations for the double taxation treaties with Jersey, Guernsey and the Isle of Man.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","191479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007164","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-21","<p>The proposed works at Windmill Bridge Junction and East Croydon form part of a wider Brighton Mainline (BML) upgrade programme, led by Network Rail.</p><p> </p><p>An Outline Business Case (OBC) is expected to be complete in late 2019. Consistent with our new Rail Enhancements Pipeline process, once the OBC is finalised, a decision will be made whether to progress and fund the Final Business Case (FBC) stage and further development of the project, leading ultimately to a final investment decision over the coming years. Our decision to deliver the programme will be based on there being a sound business case, planning permission, and overall affordability.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2018-11-21T11:03:05.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007164/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007164/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-14","Railways: Croydon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to make a decision on the Windmill Junction East Croydon grade-separated capacity enhancement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","191424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007165","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-21","<p>The Government’s £80m investment in accelerating smart ticketing builds on previous and existing franchise commitments, and sits alongside Government funding for Transport for the North’s smart ticketing programme and the Rail Delivery Group’s investment in barcode technology.</p><p> </p><p>Together, these programmes mean that the rail industry is on track to deliver a smart card or barcode option that passengers can choose to use for singles, returns and seasons on journeys across almost all of the rail network by the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2018-11-21T11:13:21.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007165/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007165/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-14","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 November 2018 to Question 183470 on Railways and Aviation: Fares, what proportion of the UK rail network passengers are planned to be able to use (a) smart cards and (b) mobile phones for fares by the end of 2018.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","191425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007166","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-22","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) works closely with its operators and the wider sector on climate change risk assessment, mitigation and resilience, including from flooding and coastal change. The UK Climate Change Risk Assessment 2017 outlines the UK’s and Devolved Government’s views on climate change risks and the National Adaption Programme published in July sets out Government’s adaption measures, including for roads and railways.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail continue to implement resilience measures to protect the railway and surrounding areas where sea level rise and increased flooding is anticipated. A project to enhance our understanding of asset criticality and the vulnerability of rail infrastructure to sea level rise is being developed to support this work. Highways England (HE) continue to embed resilience measures across its activities to maintain a fit for purpose Strategic Road Network. This includes consideration of coastal flooding and erosion risks as part of their Flood Risk Strategy and future planning to the road network.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-11-22T11:31:33.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007166/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1007166/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-14","Sea Level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 23 of the report of the Committee on Climate Change entitled Managing the coast in a changing climate, published in October 2018, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of that report's conclusions on expected sea level change; and what assessment he has made of the potential effect of such sea level changes on (a) roads and (b) railways.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","191426"
